ce:section.ce:para:
The sensitivity of the proposed method for ALP detection relies largely on the dephosphorylation of DNA primer and the subsequent polymerization reaction, so dephosphorylation reaction time, the concentration of TdT, and polymerization reaction time should be optimized to realize more sensitive and accurate detection of ALP. Under the condition of 1 ​μM solution of DNA primer, 0.2 U/L ALP, 0.3 U/μL TdT and 50 ​μM ThT, the fluorescence intensity at 495 ​nm increased along with the increase of the reaction time from 0 to 60 ​min, and then reached a plateau after 90 ​min of dephosphorylation reaction (Fig. 4
                        ). So the optimal dephosphorylation reaction time was determined to be 90 ​min. As for the amount of TdT, the relationship between the fluorescence intensity at 495 ​nm and the concentration of TdT (Fig. 5
                        ) suggested an optimal value of 0.3 U/μL. The influence of the polymerization reaction time on the fluorescence intensity was also investigated (Fig. 6
                        ). An optimal polymerization reaction time of 2 ​h was selected for subsequent experiments.
